You are a senior developer and code reviewer. I just joined a new team.
I have NO idea about their coding standards, patterns, or conventions.

Analyze their existing project and extract EVERY coding standard they follow
so I can write code that looks like THEIRS, not like an outsider.

====================================
THE PROJECT:
====================================

====================================
EXTRACT ALL OF THESE:
====================================

1. PROJECT STRUCTURE
   - How are folders organized? Draw a tree diagram
   - What is the naming convention for folders?
   - Where do they put handlers, models, services, utils, configs?
   - Is there a pattern? (MVC, Clean Architecture, Hexagonal, etc.)
   - Show: folder → purpose → example file

2. FILE NAMING
   | Pattern | Example | Rule |
   - snake_case or camelCase or kebab-case?
   - Do they suffix files? (e.g., _handler.go, _service.go, _test.go)
   - How do they name test files?
   - How do they name config files?

3. VARIABLE NAMING
   | Type | Convention | Example From Their Code |
   - Local variables: short or descriptive?
   - Global variables: how named?
   - Constants: UPPER_CASE or CamelCase?
   - Function parameters: abbreviated or full words?
   - Loop variables: i,j,k or descriptive?
   - Boolean variables: isActive, hasPermission pattern?
   - Error variables: err or specific names?

4. FUNCTION / METHOD NAMING
   | Pattern | Example | Rule |
   - Public vs private naming?
   - Verb-first? (GetUser, CreateOrder, HandleRequest)
   - How long are function names?
   - Do they use receivers? (methods on structs)
   - How do they name constructors? (New..., Create...)

5. STRUCT / TYPE NAMING
   | Pattern | Example | Rule |
   - Singular or plural?
   - How do they name interfaces?
   - How do they name custom types?
   - JSON tags: snake_case or camelCase?
   - Do they use pointer receivers or value receivers?

6. ERROR HANDLING PATTERN
   - How do they handle errors? (return, wrap, log, panic?)
   - Do they use custom error types?
   - Do they use fmt.Errorf or errors.New or custom?
   - Do they wrap errors? (fmt.Errorf("...: %w", err))
   - Show their exact error handling pattern with example

7. LOGGING PATTERN
   - What logger do they use? (log, logrus, zap, zerolog?)
   - Log format: JSON or text?
   - What log levels do they use?
   - What info do they include in logs?
   - Show their exact logging pattern with example

8. IMPORT ORGANIZATION
   - How do they order imports?
   - Do they group: stdlib / external / internal?
   - Do they use aliases?
   - Show their exact import pattern

9. CODE ORGANIZATION INSIDE FILES
   - What comes first? (constants, types, functions?)
   - Do they group related functions together?
   - How do they order methods on a struct?
   - Where do they put init() function?
   - Show their standard file layout template

10. COMMENTS & DOCUMENTATION
    - Do they comment every function?
    - What style? // or /* */
    - Do they use godoc format?
    - Do they write TODO/FIXME comments?
    - Do they document packages?
    - Show their commenting pattern

11. TESTING PATTERNS
    - How do they name tests? Test_FunctionName or TestFunctionName?
    - Do they use table-driven tests?
    - Do they use testify or standard testing?
    - Do they use mocks? What library?
    - How do they organize test helpers?
    - Do they have integration tests vs unit tests separated?
    - Show their exact test pattern with example

12. CONFIGURATION PATTERN
    - How do they manage config? (env vars, config files, flags?)
    - Do they use viper, envconfig, or custom?
    - How do they handle secrets?
    - How do they handle different environments? (dev, staging, prod)

13. DEPENDENCY INJECTION
    - Do they pass dependencies through constructors?
    - Do they use interfaces for dependencies?
    - Do they use a DI framework?
    - Show their pattern

14. API / REQUEST-RESPONSE PATTERN
    - How do they structure request/response models?
    - How do they validate input?
    - How do they format API responses? (envelope pattern?)
    - Standard HTTP status codes they use?
    - Show their pattern

15. DATABASE PATTERN
    - How do they connect to DB?
    - Do they use ORM or raw SQL?
    - How do they name tables, columns?
    - How do they handle transactions?
    - How do they handle migrations?

16. HIDDEN RULES (things nobody tells new developers)
    - Any unwritten conventions you can detect?
    - Any anti-patterns they avoid?
    - Any team-specific shortcuts or helpers?
    - Things that would make my code look "different" from theirs?

====================================
FINAL OUTPUT:
====================================

CHEAT SHEET: Give me a one-page quick reference card with ALL their 
conventions I can keep open while coding:

| Category | Their Convention | Example | Do This | Don't Do This |

STARTER TEMPLATE: Give me a blank Go file template that follows ALL 
their conventions, ready to use when I create new files.

CODE REVIEW CHECKLIST: Give me a checklist I can run through before 
submitting my code to make sure it matches their standards:
☐ File named correctly?
☐ Variables follow convention?
☐ Errors handled their way?
☐ Imports organized?
☐ Tests written their way?
☐ ...

====================================
RULES:
- Be extremely detailed, miss nothing
- Use tables for organized info
- Show REAL examples from their code, not generic ones
- If you see inconsistencies in their code, flag them
- Compare with Go community standards where relevant
- Ask "Want me to analyze more files?" at the end
====================================
